Just an hour away from downtown Bali, Uluwatu is famous for its white sand beaches that are ideal for surfing, or hanging out on a cliff top cafe to admire the scenery. 

📍Dreamsea Surf Camp

But first, let me take a selfie!
Can’t come to Bali and not visit our friends in Ubud!

Morning coffee in the rice fields 🌾🌾🌾🌾

📍Batu Karu Kopi

These past couple of days have all been about Shinrin-Yoku, the Japanese concept of nature therapy to improve mental and physical health! And what better place to do it than in the beautiful region of Munduk in north of Bali! Have you heard of Shinrin-Yoku before?

12 years ago today, we tied the knot in a travel-themed wedding 💝 Still feels like it’s just the beginning, and the best is yet to come! We are two wanderers, navigating through the ups and downs of life, in a world full of personal and professional possibilities, experiences, and joyful moments, and we would not have it any other way! Cheers to many more anniversaries in many more countries 🥂🎉🌍
Finally made it to the Philippines! First stop Boracay, and three weeks of adventure ahead!

From the more than 7,000 islands in the Philippines, Boracay is one of the easier ones to get to, which makes it quite popular! A small island of just about 10km^2, it has multiple white sand beaches with clear water and many shops and restaurants! While relatively easy to get to, checkout the steps involved.
Office view of the day! Not all Starbuckses are created equal ;) This one in Boracay comes with a magnificent view of the White Beach and its gorgeous sunset!

This is just a tiny slice from the more than 7000 beautiful islands in the Philippines! 

📍CYC Beach, Coron
The raw beauty of the Philippines is jaw dropping!

Ideal for a quick stop, this secluded beach next to the famous Secret Lagoon in El Nido, definitely gives you Castaway vibes! But luckily just around the corner you can buy fresh coconuts to sip on, and hop on to your boat to hit other nearby islands.
When in the Philippines! Tag who you would like to share a fresh coconut with 🥥💦

Beauty around every corner in the Philippines! Don’t miss the crystal clear freshwater Kayangan Lake in Coron! 

This is just the arrival point, and from here you go up a short hike to reach a jaw dropping viewpoint. You then climb down to the other side to reach the lake. 

To beat the crowds, need to go super early or around noon, when most tours are on lunch breaks in other locations.

location.city_name: Twin Lagoon, Coron Islands Palawan, Philippines

social_posts.post_text: Kayaking around the Twin Lagoon! How gorgeous is the scenery! It’s one of the most popular stops in the boat tours, and you can rent kayaks in the harbor of Coron and take it with you on the tour, or just swim through it. To beat the crowds, we suggest booking a private tour so they drop you off when others have not shown up yet, which is usually earlier in the day.

Our 1000th post!! To mark this milestone, we will do a little reintroduction for everyone who’s new here: 

We are a globetrotting digital nomad couple that left the US in 2017 and traveled the world full-time and lived out of our suitcases up to just recently, when we chose the center of the world, Istanbul, as our base. We’ve traveled  through, and lived and worked in more than 70 countries. We’ve become slow travelers and enjoy absorbing the local culture of the places we visit. We work full-time remotely, which gives us the freedom to see the world! 

In this picture, we are sitting on a traditional Filipino hut, where we slept on a deserted island, while on a three day sea expedition from Coron to El Nido, Philippines!

Would you sleep here? This is a traditional bamboo hut called Payag that is indigenous to the Philippines. This is where we slept on a three day sea expedition that we did going from Coron to El Nido. A unique experience on a deserted island, with the sunrise and calm water as the bonus!

Breathtaking! On our way to Kayangan Lake, after about 250 steps, we got to take this view all in! 

If you time it right to arrive early in the morning or around noon, you will beat the group tours and crowds, and will be able to enjoy a more peaceful scenery and swim in a much less crowded beautiful lake!

Can’t believe it’s real!!

This is just one of the many surreal spots in the Philippines, and moments before we went snorkeling in the crystal clear waters!

Lunch in Paradise!

Although it was overcast that day, we still had an amazing  time! Our delicious lunch was prepared fresh on the boat as we were resting on the white sand! 

Before disembarking from the main port for our private island-hopping tour, our boat captain took us to a market early in the morning to buy all the food we wanted based on our preference. He helped us pick the most fresh fish and all the other ingredients. We got catch of the day, fresh veggies, noodles, the most delicious mangoes, and of course coconuts! Yummy!
Embracing serenity on the pristine waters of the Philippines!

Feeling the love for local culture and soaking in the Jeepney magic! The most popular means of public transportation in the Philippines, and a symbol of the country’s culture and art, Jeepneys are known for their crowded seating and colorful decorations! Definitely try riding one!

Welcome to Siargao, the island of palm trees!! It was so exhilarating to navigate its winding roads surrounded by lush palm trees and gorgeous scenery. Loved the landscape diversity in the Philippines!

Story time: A palm tree, a photo gone viral, and a forever changed local economy and many lives!

The bent palm tree in the background is responsible for transforming many lives! Once upon a time, village kids would use it to swing into the river. A wanderlust traveler snapped a photo of it, and the spot started to become popular with visitors who had seen the photo, which also became a symbol of Siargao’s idyllic beauty! There is now a whole local economy built around this tree! Parking fee, entrance fee, renting kayaks, fee for taking a photo on a cool bamboo raft, and little souvenir shops, all managed by the locals! In 2019, a strong typhoon broke the famous tree and many trees around it, but the villagers have been able to re-erect it with support. There is now a diving board so people won’t use the tree for their dives! The spot sees hundreds of tourists who kayak through the river, jump into the river, or just snap a memorable image. It may have become a bit too “touristy”, but arrive early and you have the place to yourself! 

📍Maasin Bridge River Swing

The first thing you notice when you land in Siargao is the endless number of palm trees! The Philippines leads the world in coconut oil exports, and Siargao with its dense canopy of coconut trees plays an undoubtably significant role. A devastating typhoon in 2019 hit the island and destroyed many of the trees, but they are regrowing and slowly regaining the island’s lush beauty. Nature’s testament to strength and renewal!
Welcome to Valbone, known as the gem of Albania due to its pristine landscapes, clear blue waters, and diverse flora and fauna. It is home to many gorgeous hikes in the Albanian Alps!
Lunch in the mountains in Valbone, Albania! Most accommodations here are local  guesthouses that offer beautiful views of the surrounding mountains!

Let’s continue our adventure through the Albanian Alps! Hiking from Valbone to Theth, two beautiful mountain villages connected by a somewhat challenging long trail with jaw-dropping scenery that makes you stop frequently to pinch yourself!

Taking a break during our hike from Valbone to Theth, surrounded by wildflowers and gorgeous views! It was a perfect spot to take in all the beauty that the Accursed Mountains, aka Albanian Alps, offers!

This awesome stray mountain dog that we met at the Valbone Pass summit followed us pretty much all the way down to Theth, and even waited on the trail and looked back every time we had to catch our breath! Only asked for love and affection in return! Amazing company that made the grueling descent a bit more tolerable!

Taking a moment to rest and refuel on the Valbone to Theth trail. Where mountains and tea blend, offering a sip of alpine serenity!
Woke up in the mountain village of Theth in the Albanian Alps! Theth is an up-and-coming location, so don’t expect big hotels, instead enjoy the quaint guesthouses run by the locals!

Santorini in October! At first we weren’t sure if we had picked the right time to go, but it was nearly perfect! The weather was warm, the water was pleasant, MUCH less people, and better prices. Our new favorite month to visit this charming romantic island!
Locals joke that there are more churches than homes in Santorini! So chances are that one would be in your background no matter where you take your picture. Such a magical island!
Which light is your favorite? Santorini in three different times: day, sunset, night! 💙
Was so happy to see the gorgeous Bougainvilleas still in full bloom in October in Santorini! These beauties definitely add an extra touch of glam to the island 💗

Dipping into serenity! Did you know that today’s Santorini, which sits on top of a caldera, is the result of a massive volcanic eruption that destroyed what was once a much larger singular island? Although dormant, Santorini is still an active volcano.

Soaking up the Santorini vibes, with the Aegean as my canvas 🩵

Interesting fact about the blue domes: From 1967 to 1974, the right-wing military regime in Greece imposed that all buildings be painted white and blue (colors of the Greek flag) to inspire patriotism and attract more tourists!
Moments from our short trip to Santorini this October 🤍
Santorini is truly beautiful at every hour! And chasing its magic is always a mesmerizing experience!!

It’s that time of the year again and we are back in Europe for its magical Christmas vibes! With the holiday spirit in full swing, many cities are fully transformed with their elaborate Christmas markets. Colmar in France is one of our favorites. With multiple intimate markets, marvelous decorations, and gingerbread-looking houses that you really want to take a bite of, Colmar turns into a real-life fairytale town! 

Save it for your next Christmas travel 🎄

Let us take you to one of our favorite Christmas markets! This is Cologne, Germany, which has seven lavishly decorated markets in close proximity of each other that you can visit to enjoy the magic!
Dating back to 1820, each market has a distinct theme, but all are filled with charming stalls selling food and Christmas decorations! And the ice skating rink is one of the best ones we’ve seen!
Hot chocolate to keep me warm while checking out the  intimate Christmas market in Rothenburg ob der Tauber. A charming medieval town in Germany that we have been wanting to visit for a while now!

Took a dip in a mystical geothermal lagoon in Iceland for my birthday this year! Truly grateful to celebrate another year on our gorgeous planet and absorb so much of its inspiring beauty. While on paper I may be a year older, soaking in this “fountain of youth” at the Sky Lagoon certainly made me feel younger 🥰🥂

It really feels like a fairytale town! With a Christmas museum, a year-round Christmas store, and an intimidate Christmas market, Rothenburg ob der Tauber in Germany is a medieval small town that will steal your heart with its charm! Merry Christmas and Happy Holidays everyone 🎄✨🎅🏻
So much deliciousness at the German Christmas markets! From many different sausages (wurst) to all sorts of sweets and drinks, your tummy won’t be disappointed! What would you pick?

I LOVE snow, how about you? I could not contain my excitement when Reykjavik transformed into a winter wonderland! Loved  being snow-kissed and surrounded by graceful swans that were swimming in the unfrozen part of the city’s pond. So serene! And it only took about 5 minutes to be covered in snow like this ❄️😅

2024 🥂Warm wishes from freezing Iceland! May this year bring you closer to achieving your dreams✨

The celebration in Reykjavik was incredible! It was intimidate, not too crowded, we were in the middle of the fireworks, and they went on nonstop for at least an hour! The videos definitely don’t do it any justice. And when midnight struck, the iconic Hallgrimskirkja church was lit with the colors of Iceland’s flag. The amazing thing is that all the fireworks are purchased by the people from the SAR-teams (Search and Rescue) since it is an important source of income for them who are all volunteers. People apparently spend millions on it every year, basically supporting the important volunteers in Iceland! 

Also another cool New Year’s tradition in Iceland is setting up bonfires around the country on New Year’s Eve to burn away the old year and start off with a clean slate! 

Swipe to see some of the moments 🎆🔥

The waterfalls of Iceland are gorgeous no matter when you visit, and perhaps in winter there is something magical about them that is hard to describe! Just the raw force of nature combined with the snow and icicles! This is the Skogafoss waterfall, about a two hour drive from the capital. You can walk easily right up to the fall (you will get wet 😅) or even go up the many steps to get to the top of it and have an amazing view of the powerful Skogafoss. It is quite majestic!

The Blue Lagoon in Iceland needs no introduction, but why is it blue and what is its origin story?!

The captivating Blue Lagoon in Iceland gets its mesmerizing blue hue from silica-rich, geothermally heated sea water that beautifully blends nature and technology amidst a stunning lava field!

To generate electricity from steam at the nearby Svartsengi power plant, sea water is pumped over 1,800 meters deep into the earth. As a result of interacting with the earth’s crust, the water is brought to a boiling temperature while also becoming mineral rich. The steam is then directed to the power plant and the now mineral-rich water is pumped to the Blue Lagoon. 

Interestingly, the Blue Lagoon was not intentionally built. The discharge water of the power plant formed a lagoon as it flowed into the surrounding lava field. Over time, people discovered the benefits of bathing in the warm, mineral-rich water, leading to the development of the Blue Lagoon as a popular geothermal spa, which officially opened to the public in the early 1980s and it has since become one of Iceland’s most iconic attractions!

Iceland has so many outworldy landscapes! Here we are sitting on unique basal columns on Reynisfjara beach that were formed by lava cooling down and solidifying into these hexagonal shapes! The surrounding black sand beach, the roaring waves, and the seabirds soaring above truly add to this natural masterpiece!

You can find these basal coloumns all over Iceland aging from thousands to millions of years, which is truly mesmerizing when you think about it!! They are also a source of inspiration for the design of Reykjavik’s iconic landmark the Hallgrimskirkja church.

You have to see it to believe it! A volcanic black sand beach filled with ice!! These diamond-like icebergs have drifted from a nearby glacier and have washed ashore, where they playfully interact with each wave. Definitely one of our favorite stops on our roadtrip in Iceland, and we got so lucky with the sun making it even more gorgeous. Probably the most unique beach we have seen! 

#iceland #icelandroadtrip #diamondbeach #visiticeland #traveltheworld

After multiple nights of bad luck hunting for the Northern Lights, (December is not the best month for seeing the auroras because of high cloud coverage) we were finally able to unexpectedly see this magnificent natural phenomenon when we were staying at a remote location on the southern coast of Iceland. The aurora tracking apps we used unexpectedly sent an alert that we may be able to see them in the next hour, so we jumped out, and boom!! We were totally mesmerized by it! 

Northern lights are basically our sun flexing its muscles by sending solar winds that interact with the earth’s atmosphere and magnetic field! Nature’s light show at its best! 

In reality, the camera picked up much more vibrant colors than what we saw with our eyes, because the sensor captures more wavelengths and you have to do long exposure specially if solar activity is not high. Nevertheless, an amazing sight that was certainly worth spending many nights outside in the cold, looking at the empty sky and hoping for magic to happen!
